"An what's the worst that can happen? They break an arm? Oh well." Right, because a broken arm is hardly an inconvenience, let alone painful, debilitating and carries the risk of future medical complications. I'm not saying don't let your kids climb trees, but the nonchalant way she said that kinda disturbed me. Christian has a point when she says free range parenting comes from a place of privilege. Imagine how privileged you would have to be, especially in the US with our LOVELY health care system, to think a broken arm isn't a big deal. Broken bones can bankrupt people in this country...

Also, she said something about no longer being a parent after her kids turn 18/move out of the house. That's not how it works...once a parent, always a parent. You still think about/are worried about your kids even after they've grown up; maybe less so than when they were children, but the protective, nurturing feelings don't ever really go away. Being "a parent" doesn't go away even if, god forbid, your child DIES. Your relationship with your child may change over time, but at the end of the day they are still your child.

snippet.textDisplay:
I feel like a lot of things depend on the age of the kids. Because they kept saying kids and children.. which I suppose refers to non teens since most of them have younger kids. But teenagers are also kids too so depends on the age.. and all kids are different so some things might work and some may not.

And I don't understand why there isn't a middle parent though? The word strict and free-range imply that those are 2 opposite types but there should be a middle too, because I feel like I was/am raised like that.
I'm 17, so I'm still a "kid" and I feel like I had a bit of both (according to their definitions). I was spanked, hit, beaten whatever you wanna call it yes - didn't like it though and I have bad memories from it (beating part not spanking) & it put a barrier between my relationship with my parents but I'm also kinda grateful for it at the same time because I'd say I'm a sensible person. BUT I was only spanked until about 12yrs old.. soo the teenage years were more "free-range" for me. I still had rules of course, and I questioned them. And once I understood why, I didn't have to be reminded of them to follow them. (I'm at Uni now - far away from my parents and I still follow some rules because I understand it).
I was allowed to make SOME of my decisions as a teenager and my parents made some of them. I always questioned to know why.. sometimes they told me and sometimes they didn't, so I had to figure it out myself.

My point is, i feel like there should be a bit of both. And like they said - parenting is kinda trial and error - so you can't really know what's best and what's not. And even if you figure something out, it might only work up until a certain age. There's no ULTIMATE way because there will always be downsides.
(It'll be cool to hear from the kids a few years later, how their parents parenting affected them)

IMHO, Parents should't be too strict neither too lenient. It't finding the sweet spot in between that's hard.

"Training" is a good word. For me it means to constantly patiently teach until the child gets it. Like parents train a baby to raise their heads, then to roll over, then to sit, then to stand up then walk.

Parenting styles change as the child grows:

As kids - commanding, telling what's right and wrong, how to be an independent human.

As teens - coaching, parents in the background, calling out when somethings good or needs to be improved.

As adults - Counseling. Gives advice when child called out for help

snippet.textDisplay: As a kid i grew up with semi-strict parents and im glad they were this way...and i only realized that after i turned 20...As a kid your brain is very malleable and immature to make almost any decision by yourself...Your parents have a bit more experience in a lot of things...You don't consider the consequences of your choices as a kid...My father always pushed me to learn the piano in my case, he put me into music school since i was 6...I didn't really enjoy having to study more than my friends cause i had to study homework and piano same day, but as the years passed i started realizing what a gift that was from my father...After i turned 16 i started loving music a lot and was glad that i got to learn the piano and some other instruments because now i can chase my dream with some really good experience in music since im now 23 and i played the piano since i was 6 thats 17 years of music experience and im only 23 years old...Thats huge for me and it was a gift from my father that i want able to understand at that time. I had balance with my parents, my father was strict to an extend but my mom was more open to hearing what i had to say and bonded emotionally more with me. from age 16 and up my father also started being more relaxed with me and treated me more like a man as the years passed...I would get an occasional ass whopping every now and then if i did something really bad but that stopped at 16. And im also very glad for the manners they taught me...to help people,never do good to your self by harming others,being polite etc. things a lot of people around me dont have... So to be honest i think being a bit strict is necessary for a kid to grow up being a respectable person at the least and free range parenting is the most awful thing i have heard in my life...like its even worse than very strict parenting...at least with very strict parenting you are almost guaranteed to do something in your life even tho you may be mentally scarred and have some issues but with free range parenting you need to be extremely lucky for your kid to even survive these days...

snippet.textDisplay: I feel like there is a level of how strict you should be. I don't entirely believe in 100% free range. But rather than figuratively "always having your foot in the door" of your kids entire life, parents should definitely have a figurative "key". My parents let me do what I pleased, but if they were under the impression that I was in danger to myself or others, it would take them 2 seconds to get access to my methods of communication and likely where I am currently located. And they had a strict understanding that, mutually clear communication was always the first step before prying and "tiger parenting" (being the last resort).
